oken=3DfJAFmUDAlkg4ILGHh1B5XejspTPtf-52cWi5MO9158nyP1WX8db6G0x2AkL1-ba7HVCo=
E5zNCRzQE9744vbfAe6ZRhz3w4Wai67I5w1oB38%3D

John Murphy

For years it has traded accountability reforms in contract negotiations wit=
h the city for compensation and limiting civilian oversight.  Recent report=
ing said Seattle=E2=80=99s newer SPOG contract still left several accountab=
ility reforms unimplemented, including limits involving discipline appeals,=
 subpoena powers, complains time limits, and other oversight mechanisms app=
roved years earlier. =20

Compensation increases and reform provisions were linked in negotiations, i=
.e. pay us more and we'll comply with restrictions and oversight.  Seattle=
=E2=80=99s police union repeatedly used contract negotiations to preserve d=
isciplinary protections and limit some oversight reforms while also securin=
g higher compensation.

Only a small number of U.S. cities offer higher starting salaries than Seat=
tle Police's entry-level officer pay of $103,944.  Starting salary also com=
es with a hiring bonus of  $7,500 to $50,000 depending on experience.  Alon=
g with that Seattle has a gold-plated retirement benefits plan.  And then t=
here's overtime where Seattle not surprisingly has unusually high overtime =
costs and generous overtime rules, especially compared with many other city=
 departments.  And because Seattle Police Department is undermaned, staffin=
g shortages drive mandatory or abundant voluntary OT driving up costs even =
more. That overtime income is then used to further increase pension benefit=
s.  Hundreds of Seattle's police made $200k+/yr in total compensation - som=
e even making that much just in overtime - and then retire with a fat benef=
it plan.

And for all this we're getting what?

